04897nam a22007935i 9780231520836DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009025303  a(OCoLC)1013935538  a(OCoLC)1029815106  a(OCoLC)979620429  a97802315208367 a10.7312/ocam150142doi  a(DE-B1597)459177  a(OCoLC)811408450  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHC59.7b.O263 2009 4aHC59.7 ǂb O263 2009eb 7aBUS0720002bisacsh04a338.9009172/41 aOcampo, José Antonio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrowth and Policy in Developing Countries :bA Structuralist Approach /cJosé Antonio Ocampo, Lance Taylor, Codrina Rada. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInitiative for Policy Dialogue at Columbia: Challenges in Development and Globalization00tFrontmatter -- tThe Initiative for Policy Dialogue at Columbia -- t1. Economic Structure, Policy, and Growth -- t2. Growth and Policy Space in Historical Terms -- t3. Growth Rates, Economic Structures, and Energy Use -- t4. Open Economies and Patterns of Trade -- t5. Patterns of Net Borrowing in Open Developing Economies -- t6. Financial Structures -- t7. Macroeconomic Policy Choices -- t8. Growth and Sectoral Policy -- t9. Stylized Facts and Policy Alternatives -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEconomic structuralists use a broad, systemwide approach to understanding development, and this textbook assumes a structuralist perspective in its investigation of why a host of developing countries have failed to grow at 2 percent or more since 1960. Sensitive to the wide range of factors that affect an economy's strength and stability, the authors identify the problems that have long frustrated growth in many parts of the developing world while suggesting new strategies and policies to help improve standards of living.After a survey of structuralist methods and post-World War II trends of global economic growth, the authors discuss the role that patterns in productivity, production structures, and capital accumulation play in the growth dynamics of developing countries. Next, it outlines the evolution of trade patterns and the effect of the terms of trade on economic performance, especially for countries that depend on commodity exports. The authors acknowledge the structural limits of macroeconomic policy, highlighting the negative effects of financial volatility and certain financial structures while recommending policies to better manage external shocks. These policies are then further developed through a discussion of growth and structural improvements, and are evaluated according to which policy options-macro, industrial, or commercialbest fit within different kinds of developing economies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic developmentzDeveloping countries. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh1 aRada, Codrina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTaylor, Lance, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/ocam1501440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231520836423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231520836/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  a